10. Why files are organized this way
Backend Structure Rationale:

/core — Shared Infrastructure

Why separate: Config and security are cross-cutting concerns
Used by: all routes, workers, and db
Isolation: changes don't cascade to individual routes
/api/routes — Route Modules

Why separate files: Each route module is independent
Scalability: Can add routes without affecting others
Testing: Test each route in isolation
Naming: /routes indicates HTTP API contracts
/ingestion — Data Pipeline

Why separate: External API calls (RSS, SEC, market data)
Concern: Fetching external data
Fault isolation: Failed feed doesn't crash system
/processing — NLP & Business Logic

Why separate: AI/ML operations are distinct from data fetching
Reusability: Called from routes + workers
Testing: NLP components tested separately
/workers — Async Task Queue

Why separate: Background jobs run outside request/response cycle
Concern: Long-running operations
Isolation: Worker failures don't affect API availability
/db — Data Layer

Why separate: All database operations centralized
Abstraction: Routes don't know SQL directly
Testability: Mock database layer in tests
Frontend Structure Rationale:

/pages — Route Pages

Why: Each page maps to a route in React Router
Clarity: Quick to find page for given URL
Scalability: Add pages without touching other pages
/components — Reusable UI Blocks

Why: Componentization = React best practice
Reusability: SeverityBadge used in 5+ places
Maintenance: Update component once, affects everywhere
/api — Data Fetching Layer

Why: Centralized API client (not scattered in components)
Consistency: All requests use same interceptors
Testing: Mock API layer in tests
React Query hooks: Automatic caching/refetching
/store — Global State

Why: Zustand for auth + UI state
Clarity: Not scattered in component props
Testability: Can test store independently
/utils — Helper Functions

Why: Reusable utilities (date formatting, etc.)
Single Responsibility: Utilities don't depend on React
